#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Crosswind Circuits",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 2 — Stage C2B | E8, E11, E12",
  author: "C.Moroney",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Crosswind Circuits]

,aim: [
Conduct takeoffs, circuits, and landings in crosswind conditions of 5–15 knots using correct crosswind technique throughout.
]

,overview: [
Stage C2B is conducted when crosswind conditions of 5–15 knots are present, either concurrently with or after C2A depending on weather. It introduces drift correction on all circuit legs, crosswind takeoff technique, and crosswind approach and landing. Training is conducted in crosswind up to 15 knots — the aircraft crosswind limit. Solo authorisation in crosswind is available from 5–8 knots only; C2B must be demonstrated to S standard on two separate flights in that range before crosswind solo is permitted. Above 8 knots crosswind, training continues dual only. The student independently obtains the weather briefing from NAIPS; the instructor continues to sign the maintenance release while the student reviews and briefs it.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Explain the effect of crosswind on circuit tracking on every leg
- Describe crosswind takeoff technique: into-wind aileron, rudder for centreline control
- Describe the wing-down (forward-slip) approach and the crabbed approach; when each is appropriate
- Explain the aircraft crosswind limit and how to find it in the POH
- Explain the effect of wind gradient on a crosswind approach
- Describe how to calculate the crosswind component from NAIPS wind data

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Apply wind correction angle on all circuit legs to maintain correct ground track
- Conduct a crosswind takeoff with correct aileron and rudder technique
- Conduct a crosswind approach and landing using wing-down or crabbed technique
- Maintain directional control through the crosswind hold-off and rollout; apply into-wind aileron
- Calculate crosswind component from NAIPS TAF wind data independently

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] Monitor wind throughout; adjust correction angle as conditions change; recognise gusts and respond immediately
- [TEM] Identify crosswind as a threat multiplier; know and respect the aircraft crosswind limit; set a personal limit below the aircraft limit
- [HF] Manage increased cognitive load of crosswind correction on top of normal circuit workload; prioritise aircraft control
- [CRM] Brief crosswind component and technique selection to instructor before every approach
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aerodynamics — sideslip, cross-controlled flight *(Pg 105, 167)*
- Human Factors — SA, stress management *(Pg 3, 36–37)*
- Air Legislation — VMC *(Pg 90)*
- Refer POH for crosswind limit
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 30 minutes \
Equipment required: Whiteboard, runway diagram, aircraft model \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Crosswind as a threat multiplier: increased demands during an already high-workload phase; know the aircraft limit (15 kt); solo is only permitted in 5–8 kt crosswind; set a personal limit
- [SA] Monitor wind continuously during flight; gusts require immediate correction; recognise when conditions are deteriorating
- [HF] Crosswind correction adds cognitive load on top of the normal circuit — prioritise aircraft control; brief technique before each approach

*Crosswind Effect on Circuit Tracking* (5 minutes)
- Drift affects every leg: apply wind correction angle; adjust continuously using LARI scan
- Downwind: angle into wind to maintain parallel track; adjust if wind changes

*Crosswind Takeoff* (5 minutes)
- Into-wind aileron before roll; maintains wings level against crosswind lift tendency
- Rudder for centreline throughout roll; do not allow weathercocking
- Gradually release aileron as speed increases; aircraft becomes more directionally stable
- Lift off wings-level; track runway centreline extended; apply wind correction on climbout

*Crosswind Approach Techniques* (10 minutes)
- Wing-down (forward-slip): into-wind aileron to prevent drift; opposite (downwind) rudder for runway alignment; slight bank at touchdown; upwind wheel touches first
- Crabbed approach: maintain crab angle throughout; enter forward-slip just before the runway; touch down aligned with runway, upwind wheel first
- Both techniques are acceptable; wing-down provides earlier alignment; crabbed may feel more natural initially; choose one and brief it before each approach

*Post-Touchdown Crosswind Control* (5 minutes)
- Into-wind aileron applied immediately after touchdown; prevents upwind wing from lifting in the crosswind
- Aileron effectiveness increases as speed decreases — continue applying throughout rollout
- Rudder maintains directional control; prevent weathercocking; do not allow aircraft to veer or induce a PIO
- If using toe brakes, establish directional control before using the brakes
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Review maintenance release with student; sign the release
- Review NOTAMs with student; student to identify any relevant items
- Check student's weather brief including crosswind component calculation

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Access NAIPS independently; obtain TAF/GAF/GPWT; calculate crosswind component; brief to instructor
- Check BOM radar as supplemental; note any weather approaching
- Review NOTAMs with instructor assistance; identify relevant items
- Review maintenance release with instructor; brief any items of note before instructor signs
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and operations whiteboard
- Lead pre-flight inspection independently
- Deliver pre-takeoff safety brief before taxi; include crosswind technique selection and EFATO plan
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- Instructor demonstrates one crosswind circuit including takeoff, drift correction on all legs, approach, and landing — patter corrections throughout
- Highlight drift on downwind; demonstrate crab angle or sideslip on final; demonstrate hold-off and crosswind landing rollout
- Instructor demonstrates one additional crosswind landing using the technique not used in the first demonstration. The student should have been demonstrated both the wing-down and crabbed method

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- Crosswind takeoff: into-wind aileron before roll; rudder for centreline; release aileron progressively
- Circuit tracking: wind correction angle applied on each leg; adjust and verbalise corrections
- Gate assessment: 300 ft criteria assessed every approach; go-around if not met
- Approach: technique briefed before turning final; drift controlled; airspeed correct; gate met at 300 ft
- Landing: crosswind technique maintained through hold-off; into-wind aileron throughout rollout; directional control
- Touch-and-go: reconfigure and apply crosswind technique on subsequent takeoff
- Go-around: executed without hesitation if approach becomes unstable or crosswind control is lost
- Minimum 4 circuits across one or more sessions in crosswind conditions; conducted in progressively stronger crosswind as proficiency develops, up to 15 kt aircraft limit
]

,common_errors:[
- *Using the nose for alignment*: Use body (chest or legs) to judge alignment; parallax error from left seat affects nose reference.
- *Using rudder for drift correction*: Aileron corrects for drift; rudder keeps the aircraft straight — do not confuse them.
- *Insufficient into-wind aileron on rollout*: Apply and maintain after touchdown; the upwind wing will lift if not held.
- *No drift correction in circuit*: Apply correction angle and hold; do not chase the runway with frequent heading changes.
- *Airspeed fixation*: Attitude is the primary indication; especially in gusty conditions; do not chase the airspeed indicator.
- *Misjudging student ability*: Do not push students so far outside their skill level that they feel defeated. Constant control intervention does not help student; consider another activity if student progress is regressing.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Review each landing; identify where drift control was effective and where it broke down.
- *Instructor Feedback* (10 min):
  - Review crosswind component on the day; was technique appropriate?
  - Identify specific points where drift correction was lost; provide correction cues.
  - Assess gate compliance and go-around decision quality under crosswind pressure.
- *Weather debrief* (2 min): Was crosswind component calculated correctly? Did conditions change during the session?
- *Next Steps*: Record progress. C2B S standard (for solo) requires two separate flights in 5–8 kt crosswind. Training continues dual to 15 kt.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
*Note: S standard on two separate flights in 5–8 kt crosswind is required for crosswind solo authorisation. Training dual continues in crosswind up to 15 kt (aircraft limit). Solo is not permitted above 8 kt crosswind.*

#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P) — continue C2B sessions*]
- *Crosswind takeoff*: Into-wind aileron applied; centreline maintained with minor deviations; technique improving
- *Circuit tracking*: Wind correction applied on most legs; occasional drift with self-correction
- *Gate assessment*: Gate assessed at 300 ft with occasional prompting; go-around initiated when gate not met
- *Landing*: Crosswind landing completed safely; may require prompting on aileron application during rollout
- *Weather*: NAIPS TAF/GAF/GPWT obtained independently; crosswind component calculated with minor guidance

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required for crosswind solo authorisation; two separate flights in 5–8 kt crosswind*]
- *Crosswind takeoff*: Into-wind aileron applied consistently; centreline maintained throughout
- *Circuit tracking*: Wind correction applied proactively on all legs; minimal drift
- *Gate assessment*: All four criteria assessed at 300 ft every approach; gate met or go-around initiated without prompting
- *Landing*: Technique selected and briefed; drift controlled throughout approach; airspeed +5/−0 kts; into-wind aileron maintained through rollout
- *Go-around*: Initiated proactively when approach unstable; no prompting
- *Weather*: NAIPS TAF/GAF/GPWT obtained and interpreted independently; crosswind component calculated correctly

- *Outcome*: Recorded as P, S, or NC per session with specific comments. S standard in 5–8 kt crosswind noted separately from dual-only training in stronger conditions.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Ceiling >1500 ft AGL; crosswind 5–15 knots for dual training in C2B; solo is not permitted in crosswind >8 knots. Visibility >8 km.
- *Aircraft limit*: 15 kt crosswind is the aircraft limit; do not exceed in training
- *Solo limit*: Crosswind solo is only authorised in 5–8 kt crosswind; above 8 kt, dual training only
- *Altitude*: Strict circuit height; monitor base-to-final — crosswind can cause the turn to become steeper than intended
- *Emergency Procedures*: EFATO brief before each takeoff
- *TEM*:
  - Crosswind significantly increases landing risk — maintain heightened alert monitoring throughout approach and hold-off
  - Take control immediately if directional control is lost on landing or if aircraft weathercocks on rollout
  - Monitor student fatigue — crosswind sessions are cognitively demanding; limit to 8 circuits per session
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aerodynamics: Pg 105, 167 (sideslip, skid and slip)
  - Human Factors: Pg 3, 36–37 (SA, stress management)
  - Air Legislation: Pg 90 (VMC requirements)
- Practise calculating crosswind component from wind data using a wind component chart
- Reflect:
  - "How would you decide between a crabbed and wing-down approach? What conditions influence your choice?"
  - "What would you do if a strong gust caused you to drift off centreline on short final?"
]
)

